FILE: Protesters hold placards during a protest to show their support to fellow miners who filed a lawsuit against mining companies, Johannesburg, 13 October 2015. JOHANNESBURG - The Gauteng High Court has approved the historic R5-billion settlement agreement in the silicosis case. Legal process involved gold miners affected with the lung disease since 1965. Claimants will be paid out between R70,000 and R500,000 each. WATCH: New mining charter released The historic R5-billion settlement was reached in 2018 after three years of extensive negotiations between the companies and the claimants' attorneys. The six mining companies are African Rainbow Minerals, Anglo American SA, AngloGold Ashanti, Gold Fields, Harmony and Sibanye-Stillwater – and attorneys Richard Spoor Inc, Abrahams Kiewitz Inc and the Legal Resources Centre who represented thousands of mineworkers and their dependents.